a + 2b &= 14,\\
a + 2c &= 16.
\end{align*}
From these two equations, we can solve for $a$:
\begin{align*}
a &= 14 - 2b,\\
a &= 16 - 2c.
\end{align*}
Equating the two expressions for $a$, we get:
\begin{align*}
14 - 2b &= 16 - 2c,\\
-2b + 2c &= 2,\\
-b + c &= 1,\\
c &= b + 1.
\end{align*}
Now we substitute $c = b + 1$ into one of the equations for $a$:
\begin{align*}
a &= 14 - 2b.
\end{align*}
